  "SIMULATION FAILED - %0d MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME %0d"  ,  "SIMULATION PASSED"  :  "SIMULATION PASSED"  ,  "SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y"  :  "SIMULATION FAILED - %0d MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME %0d"  ,  "SIMULATION PASSED"  :  "SIMULATION PASSED"  ,  "SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y"  :  "SIMULATION FAILED - %0d MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME %0d"  }')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text="Json Decode Error: Required key 'interface' missing from model output. Available keys: ['reasoning', 'SIMULATION PASSED', 'y', 'x', 'SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y']")]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "1. **Module Implementation (`TopModule`):** The specification requires detecting any edge (0->1 or 1->0) for each bit of an 8-bit input `in` and outputting this one cycle late. This requires storing the previous input value. Since the testbench uses a reference module (`RefModule`) to provide the expected output, I must implement the logic to match the reference module\'s behavior (which is the ground truth). The logic for edge detection is: $anyedge[i] = (\\text{in}[i] \\neq \\text{prev_in}[i])$. Since the output must be delayed by one clock cycle, the register holding the output must be updated based on the current input and the stored previous input. I will use a register to store the previous input state.\\n\\n2. **Interface:** The golden testbench instantiates `TopModule` using: `clk` (input), `in` (input, 8 bits), and `anyedge` (output, 8 bits). I must match this signature exactly.\\n\\n3. **Testbench Improvement:**\\n    a. **Sequential Nature:** `TopModule` is sequential, so I must implement queue-based mismatch checking.\\n    b. **Queue Sizing:** The input width is 8 bits. The requirement suggests a size based on pattern length + 1. I will set `MAX_QUEUE_SIZE` to 10, adhering to the constraint and accommodating the required delay/pattern length.\\n    c. **Queue Logic:** I will create queues for `in`, `anyedge_dut` (actual output), `anyedge_ref` (expected output), and since the original testbench used `tb_match`, I will track mismatches based on this.\\n    d. **Error Handling:** The original error counting logic (tracking `stats1.errors` and `stats1.errors_anyedge`) must be maintained. The queue mechanism will replace the simple error counting, but the final summary display must conform to the required format based on whether any mismatches occurred.\\n    e. **Display:** The queue logic will be implemented in an `always @(posedge clk, negedge clk)` block to ensure synchronized logging. Upon the first mismatch, it will print the queue contents. At the end, it will print either \\"SIMULATION PASSED\\" or the specific failure message: \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\".\\n    f. **Golden Testbench Modification:** The original testbench uses a complex structure involving `stats1`. I will replace this structure with the queue-based logic, while ensuring the clocking and the core comparison (`tb_match`) remain functionally equivalent to the original structure.\\n\\n4. **Syntax Advice:** Ensure all ports are declared as `logic` in the interface and testbench for modern SystemVerilog compliance. The sequential logic in `TopModule` must correctly use non-blocking assignments (`<=`) triggered by `posedge clk` to satisfy the synchronous requirement.\\n\\n*Self-Correction/Refinement during queue implementation*: The original testbench counts errors continuously. The queue implementation must achieve the same count while providing the detailed state dump only on the *first* mismatch. I will use a flag to track if the first mismatch has already been reported.",\n    "interface": "module TopModule (input logic clk, input logic [7:0] in, output logic [7:0] anyedge);\\nendmodule",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\\n`define OK 12\\n`define INCORRECT 13\\n\\n// --- Stimulus Generator (Copied from Golden TB) ---\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n\\tinput clk,\\n\\tinput tb_match,\\n\\toutput reg [7:0] in,\\n\\toutput reg[511:0] wavedrom_title,\\n\\toutput reg wavedrom_enable\\n);\\n\\n\\t// Add two ports to module stimulus_gen:\\n\\t//    output [511:0] wavedrom_title\\n\\t//    output reg wavedrom_enable\\n\\n\\ttask wavedrom_start(input[511:0] title = \\"\\");\\n\\tendtask\\n\\t\\n\\ttask wavedrom_stop;\\n\\t\\th#1;\\n\\tendtask\\t\\n\\n\\tinitial begin\\n\\t\\tin <= 8\'h00;\\n\\t\\t@(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t@(negedge clk) wavedrom_start(\\"\\");\\n\\t\\trepeat(2) @(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\tin <= 8\'h01;\\n\\t\\trepeat(4) @(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\tin <= 8\'h00;\\n\\t\\trepeat(4) @(negedge clk);\\n\\t\\tin <= 8\'h06;\\n\\t\\trepeat(2) @(negedge clk);\\n\\t\\tin <= 8\'h00;\\n\\t\\trepeat(2) @(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t@(negedge clk) wavedrom_stop();\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\trepeat(200)\\n\\t\\t\\t@(posedge clk, negedge clk) in <= $random;\\n\\t\\t$finish;\\n\\tend\\n\\nendmodule\\n\\n// --- Reference Model (Assuming this is the expected behavior) ---\\nmodule RefModule (\\n\\tinput logic clk,\\n\\tinput logic [7:0] in,\\n\\toutput logic [7:0] anyedge\\n);\\n\\n\\tlogic [7:0] prev_in;\\n\\n\\talways @(posedge clk)\\n\\tbegin\\n\\t\\tprev_in <= in;\\n\\t\\t// Detect edge: (current != previous) AND (not current == previous)\\n\\t\\t// Since we are checking for transition (0->1 or 1->0), this is simply in != prev_in\\n\\t\\tanyedge <= in ^ prev_in;\\n\\tend\\n\\nendmodule\\n\\n// --- DUT Implementation (TopModule) ---\\nmodule TopModule (\\n\\tinput logic clk,\\n\\tinput logic [7:0] in,\\n\\toutput logic [7:0] anyedge\\n);\\n\\n\\t// Internal state to hold the previous input value for edge detection\\n\\tlogic [7:0] prev_in;\\n\\n\\t// The output must be set ONE cycle AFTER the transition occurs.\\n\\t// If transition happens at time T (based on input in(T)), the output should be 1 at T+1.\\n\\tlogic [7:0] next_anyedge;\\n\\n\\talways @(posedge clk)\\n\\tbegin\\n\\t\\tprev_in <= in;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t// Calculate the edge detection based on the *new* prev_in (which is the old \'in\')\\n\\t\\t// Edge detection occurs when in != prev_in\\n\\t\\t// next_anyedge should reflect the edge detected in the current clock edge, \\n\\t\\t// which means it should be present in the NEXT clock edge\'s output.\\n\\t\\tnext_anyedge <= in ^ prev_in;\\n\\tend\\n\\n\\t// Assign the delayed output (next_anyedge calculated in this cycle is visible next cycle)\\n\\talways @(posedge clk)\\n\\tbegin\\n\\t\\tanyedge <= next_anyedge;\\n\\tend\\n\\nendmodule\\n\\n// --- Testbench (Improved Golden Testbench) ---\\nmodule tb();\\n\\n\\ttypedef struct packed {\\n\\t\\tint errors;\\n\\t\\tint errortime;\\n\\t\\tint errors_anyedge;\\n\\t\\tint errortime_anyedge;\\n\\t\\tint clocks;\\n\\t} stats;\\n\\t\\n\\tstats stats1;\\n\\t\\n\\t// Queue definitions for sequential tracking\\n\\treg [7:0] in_queue [$];\\n\\treg [7:0] anyedge_dut_queue [$];\\n\\treg [7:0] anyedge_ref_queue [$];\\n\\treg reset_queue [$]; // Placeholder for structure compliance\\n\\n\\tlocalparam MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10;\\n\\t\\n\\tlogic [7:0] in;\\n\\tlogic [7:0] anyedge_ref;\\n\\tlogic [7:0] anyedge_dut;\\n\\t\\n\\t// Control signals\\n\\twire tb_match;\\n\\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\\n\\t\\n\\t// Clock generation\\t\\n\\treg clk=0;\\n\\tinitial forever\\n\\t\\th#5 clk = ~clk;\\n\\n\\t// Instantiate modules\\n\\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\\n\\t\\t.clk, clk,\\n\\t\\t.tb_match, tb_match,\\n\\t\\tin, in,\\n\\t\\twavedrom_title, wavedrom_title,\\n\\t\\twavedrom_enable, wavedrom_enable\\n\\t);\\n\\n\\tRefModule good1 (\\n\\t\\t.clk, clk,\\n\\t\\tin, in,\\n\\t\\t.anyedge, anyedge_ref\\n\\t);\\n\\t\\n\\tTopModule top_module1 (\\n\\t\\t.clk, clk,\\n\\t\\tin, in,\\n\\t\\t.anyedge, anyedge_dut\\n\\t);\\n\\n\\t// Signal assignment for verification\\n\\t// tb_match = ( { anyedge_ref } === ( { anyedge_ref } ^ { anyedge_dut } ^ { anyedge_ref } ) );\\n\\t// This simplifies to: tb_match = (anyedge_ref === anyedge_dut);\\n\\tassign tb_match = (anyedge_ref === anyedge_dut);\\n\\n\\t// Flag to ensure detailed queue display only happens once\\n\\treg first_mismatch_reported = 0;\\n\\n\\t// Task to manage queue size\\n\\ttask manage_queue;\\n\\t\\tif (in_queue.size() >= MAX_QUEUE_SIZE - 1) begin\\n\\t\\t\\tin_queue.delete(0);\\n\\t\\tanyedge_dut_queue.delete(0);\\n\\t\\tanyedge_ref_queue.delete(0);\\n\\t\\treset_queue.delete(0);\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\tendtask\\n\\n\\t// Synchronous Queue Logging and Mismatch Detection\\n\\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\tmanage_queue();\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t// Store current state\\n\\t\\tin_queue.push_back(in);\\n\\t\\tanyedge_dut_queue.push_back(anyedge_dut);\\n\\t\\tanyedge_ref_queue.push_back(anyedge_ref);\\n\\t\\treset_queue.push_back(1\'b0); // Assuming no reset signal relevant to DUT logic\\n\\n\\t\\tstats1.clocks++;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\t// Original Error Counting Logic Maintenance\\n\\t\\tif (!tb_match) begin\\n\\t\\t\\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\\n\\t\\t\\tstats1.errors++;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tif (anyedge_ref !== anyedge_dut) // Simplified comparison based on the original XOR structure\\n\\t\\tbegin \\n\\t\\t\\tif (stats1.errors_anyedge == 0) stats1.errortime_anyedge = $time;\\n\\t\\t\\tsstats1.errors_anyedge = stats1.errors_anyedge+1\'b1;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\n\\t\\t// Queue-based Mismatch Display (Only on the very first mismatch)\\n\\t\\tif (!tb_match && stats1.errors == 1 && first_mismatch_reported == 0) begin\\n\\t\\t\\t$display(\\"==================================================================================\\");\\n\\t\\t\\t$display(\\"*** FIRST MISMATCH DETECTED AT TIME %0d ***",     \n    \n    "$time);\\n\\t\\t\\t$display(\\"==================================================================================\\");\\n\\t\\t\\t$display(\\"\\\\nLast %0d 